{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945092701/0538.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL\nScientists Fear Public Naive\nAbout Atomic World Perils\nDestruction of a Nation in a Few Hours Possible\u2014Effi\ncient Defense Believed Hopeless\nN.^hyille, Tenn., Sept. 25 AP)\nAssociated Press Si; me Editor\nHoward Blakeslee said here today\nthat \"most scientists who worked on\nthe atomic bomb believe that the\nworld has changed and that the pub\nlic does not realize this.\"\nOutlining to the Nashville Rotary\nclub the attitude of scientists to whom\nhe has been talking. Blakeslee said\nthe scientists believed that \"by us\ning. more bombs, larger bombs and\nmore efficient bombs it will be pos\nsible in the near future to com\npletely destroy the bulk of the popu\niation, industry and military strength\no\u2019 any nation within a few days.\nMoreover, aviation and rocket devel\nopments might enable this to be done\nir a few hours without the possibil\nity of effective retaliation.\"\n\"Those who have discussed defense.\nIth me,\" the Pulitzer prize-winning\nscience writer said, \"say that as sci-,\nrntists they can offer no hope of a\nspecific defense against the atomic\nbomb.\u2019\u2019\nBlakeslee *aid the scientists \"fear,\nwe face a deadly peril unless the!\npublic understands.\n\"The only important difference of i\nopinion 1 have found among scien\nti>(s.\" he said, \"is the length of ^me\nbefore other nations will be able tn\nmake atomic bombs without benefit\nof our own secrets of fabrication.\n\"The estimates of this delay range\nfrom two tn 20 years. None f these\ndelays is based on secrets about the\nprinciples of a bomb. Twenty years is j\nthe minimum time estimated for other\ncountries to be able to develop an\nindustrialization comparable to that\nof the United States.\n\"The short period estimates are\n.based upon the possibility, perhaps;\nremote, but always inherent in sci-:\nence. that someone else may find a\nshort cut.\n\"Some of these men say it would be\nfoolish to suppose that scientists and\nengineers of the other countries\nwould not be able to redevelop et\nleast one of the methods which we\nhave used, or to develop new meth\nods. They add that even nations with\nlesser resources will lie able to pro\n\nfive years.\n\u201cAn aspect which has hardly been\nmentioned at all in public discussion\nis the opinion of some of the scien\ntita that a policy of secrecy, while!\n.spurring other nations, may arti-|\nficially sterilize the further develop-\u2022\nmen: of nuclear physics and chemis-!\ntry in our own country. They think;\nthis is possible becaus secrecy might!\nhave to withhold detailed information\nfrom the majority of our own scien\ntists.\u201d\nU S. SOON TO GET\nROOSEVELT\u2019S PLACE\nAT HYDEPARK, N. Y.\nLegal Transfer of Estate Will\nPut It Under Control of Na\ntional Park Service of In\nterior Department\nWashington. Sept. 25\u2014(AP)\u2014Con\ntrol of the late President Roosevelt\u2019s'\nHyde Park estate is expected to pass\nto the government as soon as family\nwaivers to occupancy of the big house\nor the Hudson are completed.\nThis was learned from family\nfriends and government officials to\nday. They said legal transfer of the J\nestate is expected to be made soon to\nthe National Park service of the in-\ntenor department. The property was\ndeeded to the government subject toi\ncertain fam \u2019y occupancy rights.\nGrave Is There. Aho\nAlong with the rambling stone-'\nstucco house and forested acres, the;\nInterior department will receive the:\nresponsibility for protecting the late]\nPresident's grave, whicu is in the;\nrose garden between the home and\nthe Roosevelt Memorial library. This'\nis now an army job. The library and'\n12 acres around it are already gov\nernment property with the national:\narchives having jurisdiction.\nPark service officials said that after\nfamily occupancy waivers ar com\npleted an appropriation will have to\nbe approved by Congress before the\ngovernment can begin to operate the\npropertv as a memorial.\nThe Roosevelt grave is still being;\nguarded by part .of the 240th military\npolice V^ttaiion which was activated;\nAugust 26, 1942, to cooperate with\nthe secret service in protecting the\nPresident while at Hydb Park.\nMP Battalion Disbanded\nThe war department said today that\n.after the death of Mr Roosevelt last\nApril 12 the secret service suggested;\nthat a full battalion was no longer]\nneeded, but asked that a small de- i\ntachment be left at Hyde Park until]\nthe interior department could take;\nover. This was described in one\nquarter today as a \"courtesy ar\nrangement.\u201d\nEXPANSION SHAKEUP\nIN COMMERCE DEPT.\nSecretary Wallace Plans to\nGive U. S. Businessmen\nMore Information\nWashington, Sept. 20 \u2014(AP) \u2014Sec-\nretary Henry A. Wallace announced\nfeorganizatlon plans for the com\nmerC\" department today to taka care\nof a broad expansion Into new fields\nof servile for business.\nHe said stress on a project for\n\u2018'analytical\" surveys designed to give I\nbusinessmen fuller information on'\ncurrent conditions and future pros-\njiects.\nThe department, the former vice\npresident said, \u201cmust be prepared to\npuli its full weight In the program\nof the administration to assure full\nprofitable production and full gainfull\nemployment.\u201d\nThe annual cost, be said, will be\nabout one-sixth of the country's daily\nwar spending, or about $42,000,000. I\nI nder the program, which was an\nnounced at a news conference, the\ndepartment will undertake to pro\nvide:\n1. A \u2018\u2018revitalized 1 foreign trade\nservice. In cooperation with the state\ndepartment, \"to promote vigorously\na high level of foreign trade on a\nsustained basis.\u201d\n2. A \"strong, balanced program\u201d of\nstatistics for business and govern\nment.\n3. A complete analytical program\nto give business and government\ncurrent Information on the economic\nsituation and business outlook.\n4 Technological aids to small busi\nness.\n3. Management aids and oth<-\nforms of direct service for busltie.-\n\u2014both large and smalt\nVICIOUS MURDER IN\nNAVY REVEALEDTO\nGET TIGHTER LAW\nRear-Admiral Gatch Reports\nSaipan Rape Attempt, With\nThree Offenders Escaping\nDeath Penalty\nWashington, Sept. 25 (AP)\nRear-Admiral Thoma* L. Gatch re\nlated a story of \"vicious, cold-blooded\nmurder\" today in winning Senate\nnaval committee approval of tighter\ncourt-martial laws.\nGatch, the judge advocate general,\ntestified:\nI \"At Saipan island last May. three\nnavy men decided to rape a woman,\niThey went down to the beach and\nthey found a navy nurse and an of-,\nificer there. They proceeded with their I\nintention. Naturally, the officer c&me\nto her defense. They machine-gunned\nI both to death.\"\nYet, for what he called \"the most\nvicious thing I have ever run aerf'se,\u201d i\nI the navy could not execute the three\nunder present laws. Gatch declaied.\nThe most they can get is life 1m-\nIprisonment for manslaughter.\nThe present law provides that \"any I\nI person belonging to any public ves- i\nI sei\u201d who commits murder outside the\njurisdiction of the United States \"may\nbe tried by court-martial and sen\ntenced to death.\"\nThe three men on Saipan were not I\nattached to any ship on duty there.!\nGatch explained, and other articles of\nthe law' so affected the article in!\nquestion that full punishment was;\nfound to be impossible.\nHe did not give the names of the\npersons involved in the ease.\nThe committee approved a change\nof wording to read that any person\nsubject to the navy who commits a\nmurder outside United States juris\ndiction may be punished with life\nimprisonment or death.\n217,575 OFF JOBS\nIN LABOR TROUBLE;\nU.S. ACTION BEGUN\nOil Strike Spreads to Six\nStates Auto Industry\nDeadlock Continues as\nConferences Start\nBy the Associated Press, Sept. 22\nThe federal conciliation service!\nyesterday tackled two prime trouble!\nspots in the reconversion labor sit-.\nnation \u2014the expanding oil workers'\nstrike and the automobile industry!\nlockout.\nAcross the nation the total num-1\nI her of idle in stoppages amounted to I\n217.575. up 12,000 from the preced\ning day.\nConciliators attempted to bring to\ngether CIO oil workers and industry;\nrepresentatives for a conference j\naimed at stopping spread of strikes\u25a0\nwhich already have nearly 19.000 per-;\nsons off the job in Indiana. Mich-!\nigan. Illinois. Ohio, West Virginia\nand Texas.\nInion Asks Conference\nThe conciliation service said the re-1\nquest for the conference was made'\nby O. A. Knight, president of the\nunion, demanding a 30 per cent wage!\nincrease.\nGasoline supplies were dwindling\nrapidly in the Toledo area after the\nGulf Oil company refinery shut down,l\nthe third to close there since Mon-|\nday. The Gulf closure left only thej\nSun Oil company refinery\" in opera-'\ni tion. It has an independent union.\nLatest of the Chicago area refin\ni cries to close was the Texas company;\nplant at Lockport, 111., where 9001\nwent out. A union leader said \"wei\nwere thrown into the strike\u201d by pick\nets from the East Chicago find. >j\nurea where four refineries were Mie.;\nIn Detroit the conciliation serv-j\nice assigned three-man panels to each!\nof several disputes which have kept,\nmore than 80.000 persons off the jolt,\nin the automobile industry.\nlAW Strikes Threatened\nA CIO United Automobile Workers'\nofficial disclosed an exchange of let\nters with General, Motors corporation\nover the union's demand tor a 30 per|\ncent wage increase. The union has:\nannounced intention to seek the!\nbust throughout the industry or call:\nstrikes, qne at a time, against each I\nof the big three car manufacturers,\nFord, Chrysler and G-M.\nChrvsler previously offered to meet;\nwith the union but there has been no\ni word from Ford. Walter Reuther.\nI UAW vice-president, said the Gen\neral Motors correspondence offered\nI to arrange meetings with the union\ni and that it was \"the first indication\nI of management\u2019s willingness to dls\ni cuss the 30 per cent demand.\u201d\nMeanwhile a transportation strike\nIwas developing in Ohio. Rudy Min-:\nI kin. secretary-treasurer of the Ohio\nConference of Teameters said a\nI strike of AFL mechanics and drivers\nhad halted operations of Trans-Amer\nican Freight Lines. inc\u201e in Ohio and\nthat it might spread to Pennsylvania\nand New York.\nThe A&P food stores announced\nthey would close 250 retail outlets in\nnorthern New Jersey and Staten Is\nland, N. Y.. tomorrow night unless;\ndeliveries were resumed from two\nNewark (N. J.) warehouses picketed\nby a clerks\u2019 union in an organlza-1\nI tional campaign.\nAmerica Urged\nTo Share Secret\nWashington. Sept 25\u2014(AP) \u2014Sen-,\nator McMahon (D-Ct) said tonight]\nthe United States could give a \u201cprac\ntical demonstration\" of its desire for\npeace by turning the atomic bomb\nsecret over to the United Nations\nsecurity council.\n\"We will allay suspicion that wo\nintend to dominate the. world.\" he said\nin an address prepared for the radio\nWe will strengthen collective secur\nity. which is the only hope of perma\nnent peace.\u201d\nMcMahon has Introduced leg'slaffon\nto establish a government board tor\ncontrol of atomic energy.\nPATTERSON <OBUlim\nWashington. Sept. 25\u2014(API\u2014The\nSenate today confirmed the appoint\nment of Robert P. Patterson of New\nYork as secretary of war. Action\nwaa by voice vote.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY. SEPTEMBER 27, 1945\n15,000 WORKERS\nAT AKRON CLOSE\n22-DAY DISPUTE\nChicago Oil Parley May Have\nGood Results\u2014New Walk-\nI outs Keep Total of Idle\nClose to 350,000\nBy the Associated Press. Sept. 25\nOne of the big labor disputes\u2014the\ni22-day rubber strike in Akron\u2014\nended yesterday and plants were\nreadied to receive 15,000 production\nworkers today.\nImportant labor developments\n[elsewhere included:\u2014\nOil Conference Begins\n1. Government, management and\nlabor representatives gathered at a\nconciliation meeting in Chicago aimed\n[at a prompt ending of the seven\nstate CIO oil workers\u2019 strike.\n2. The House ways and means\ncommittee set aside all legislation pro\nposing liberalization of unemploy\nment compensation in view of the\ncurrent wave of reconversion strikes.\n3. Nearly 30.000 coal miners in\nPennsylvania and West Virginia were\naway from the pits, supporting super\nvisors in their demand for recogni\nj tion of their union.\n4. Strike settlements, including\nthe B. F. Goodrich company dispute\nI in Akron, were offset by new disputes\nand the unofficial tabulation placed\n:he national total of persons idle in\nlabor controversies at 343,528.\nForemen End Strike\nShortly after the Goodrich company\nand the CIO United Rubber Workers\nannounced reopening of six Akron\nplants, foremen voted unanimously to\nend their three-week strike and re\nsume work.\nThe 800' foremen, members of the\nForemen's association of America,\nwalked cut Labor day. alleging the\ncompany enforced \"wholesale layoffs\"\nduring reconversion. The company\ndenied this. As a result of the fore\nmen's dispute 15,000 production em\nployes were unable to work.\nIn Chicago, Justice William L.\nKnous of the Colorado supreme court,\nhead of a three-man conciliation\npanel, said he was \"hopeful of a\nquick settlement\u201d of the CIO oil\nworkers\u2019 strike for a 30 per cent\nwage increase.\nThe strike involves 30.000 workers\nin seven states and has threatened\nsome communities with a gasoline:\nshortage.\nSecretary of Labor Schwellenbach\ntelegraphed Justice Knous \"your\nmeeting must not be permitted to\nfail.\u201d He said the oil and gasoline\nreserves would be depleted \"in a very\nfew days\u201d and that the military and\ncivilian transportation systems were\nthreatened.\nFirst Test of Policy\nThe labor-management conference\nwas the first important test of the\nTruman administration's postwar\nwage policy under a reorganized labor\ndepartment and a strengthened con\nciliation service.\nSlembers of the House ways and I\nmeans committee voiced alarm at the\nidleness in spreading strikes and\nshelved legislation proposing liberal\nization of unemployment compensa-!\n\"The strike feature was the decid\ning factor,\u201d Representative Knutson;\n(R-Minn) said, in the 14 to 10 vote\nwhich discarded President Truman's\ni equest for the legislation. The com\nmittee action postponed indefinitely\nall further consideration of jobless\npay expansion.\nA strike of supervisory workers\nclosed 45 soft coal mines in western\nPennsylvania and numerous other pits\nin northern West Virginia. The Solid\nFuels administration estimated thej\nnumber idle in Pennsylvania coal i\nfields at 21.637 and in West Virginia\nat 6000.\nThe United Clerical, Technical and j\nSupervisory Employes union, a branch j\nof the Independent United Mine?\nWorkers of America, called the strike j\nto obtain recognition of their organ\nization. Rank and file miners were\nforced into idleness by the absence of\nthe supervisors, who make safety in\nspections and manage the pits.\nAnto Negotiations Open\nIn Detroit where the United Auto\nmobile Workers are campaigning for\nan industry-wide 30 per cent wage in\ncrease. union and Chrysler corpora\ntion representatives opened confer\nences.\nAs the meetings began the union\nannounced it had asked the National\nLabor Relations board for a strike\nvote among Chrysler\u2019s 80.000 workers.,\nA vote will be taken among 300,0001\nGeneral ^fotors corporation workers:\nOctober 24 and one is planned for the\nFord Motor company, employing 109,-\n000.\nIn Toledo, 0., the Spicer corporation'\nclosed after the breakdown of nego\ntiations for wage increases for 3300\nmembers of the CIO United Automo\nbile Workers.\nLloyd Haney, company director of\nindustrial relations, declared the in\ncreases demanded amounted to 103\nper cent He said the union had\nasked that the present basic hourly\nwages be boosted 30 per cent and\nthat employes be paid for 52 hours\nalthough they would work only 30.\nHAWAII PROBERS\nVOTE SELVES TRIP\nSenate-House Group to Take\nJaunt to Pearl Harbor After\nReviewing Reports On\nEarlier Inquiries\nWashington, Sept. 25\u2014(AP) \u2014Like\na coroner\u2019s jury, the congressional\n[committee investigating Pearl Har\nbor is going to begin by taking a\nHook at the scene ot the crime.\nThe 10-member Senate-House group\n[decided at its second meeting today\n[to visit the Hawaiian naval base as\n[soon as It has completed reviewing\nI the reports made on earlier Inquiries\ninto the December 7, 1941, Japanese\nattack.\nChairman Barkley (D-Ky) said the\ntrip would:\n1. Give the members a clear con\nception of the instalatlons, surround\ning terrain and the defense establlsh\nrnents.\n2. Afford opportunity for question\ning ot witnesses who only with diffi\nculty could come to Washington for\nhearings.\nAlthough Barkley said he hoped all\nmembers would go. Senator George\n(D-Ga) said he doubted that he could.\nBecause of his heavy duties, George\nhad been reluctant to accept member\nship on the inquiry group.\nThe Pearl Harbor committee also\ndiscussed possibilities for counsel but\ntook no action. Roger Whiteford, a\nI Washington attorney, was called In\nifor an Interview. Tomorrow the\n'group will talk with William D.\nMitchell, former attorney-general\nBarkley said about 20 names were un\njder consideration.\nTwo Navy Airmen Die\nIn Collision Over Miami\nPlanes Tangle Wings Over Business District, One Falls\nThrough Warehouse Roof\u2014One Was Being Guided\nto Safe Landing\nMiami Fla., Sept. 21 \u2014(AP) A,\nnavy plane apparently in serious I\ntrouble ;md being shepherded toward\nsafety by three other navy aircraft, I\ntangled wings with a guiding aircraft\nover midtown Miami tonight, killing!\nat least two crewmen and causing a\ntwo-alarm fire in the business dis\n.l trict.\nBoth planes were from the Mel\nbourne (Fla.) naval air station. Both\nI were night fighters.\nThe troubled plane sputtered\n\u2019through the darkness over Miami!\nBeach low over crowded resort hotels, j\nattracting the attention of thousands I\n'of persons.\nLosing altitude and apparently un-\nI able to locate an airport, the plane!\nI crossed Biscayne bay and passed over j\nI the downtown section of Miami. Three\nothr planes buzzed around and\ni around the disabled machine, and one\nseemed to be guiding it, witnesses\nI reported.\ni One plane plunged through the roof\nof a hardware company\u2019s warehouse,\nsetting it and the adjoining Tuttle\nhotel garage ablaze. The garage was\nused by the coast guard.\nThe other craft crashed in the\ni street, slid across a parking lot and!\nMacArthur Plan for Japs\nSounds Soft but Won\u2019t Be\n200.000 Occupation Force Seems Small, but Man Who\nBeat Japs Understands Them\nBy W. W. WALTON\nSouth Bend. Ind., Sept. 22 \u2014CAP)\nj How big a force will it take to occupy\nJapan?\nThe furor started this week when\nGen Douglas MacArthur( allied su\npreme commander, said he could do\n[it with 200,000 men.\ni To this writer his announcement\nj came as no surprise, because Gen\nMacArthur outlined his plan to three\nof us over the luncheon table in his\nYokohama residence two days after\nthe formal surrender ceremony on the\ni battleship Missouri.\ni We were a little startled, too, and\nIraised inquiring eyebrows, but when\nthe Supreme commander had finished\nwe were wholeheartedly with him. At\nthat time, however, we couldn\u2019t tell;\nmthe world about it because the gen- j\noral was talking off the record and'\ninsisted he had to remain loyal to the i\nmore than 100 other correspondents.\nFrom what I\u2019ve heard since return\ning a few days ago, it seems that i\nmany Americans are willing to criti\ncize the general for not being more\nruthless frem the start.\nBig American Gamble\nI wonder how many of them realize i\nI just what a gamble America was\nI taking that day when less than 10.000\n\u2019marines and bluejackets scrambled!\nlashore at the Yokohama naval base;\n-while airborne troops were landing!\njat Atsugi airbase outside Yokohama.?\nThe three of us were there.\nThey were invading a country i\nwhich had a fully armed and un-\nI defeated army of 4,000,000, at least\na million of whom were on Honshu\nisland. No one knew \u2014not even Gen\nI MacArthur or Fleet Admiral Chester\n:W. Nimitz \u2014what the reaction would\n|be. They had been assured by the:\n'imperial government that the occu-\nj parion would be without resistance.:\ni But Japan is filled with fanatical\nI young men\u2014like those who piloted\nthe kamikaze planes. That army is\n[still being disarmed and Gen Mac-\nArthur is biding his time.\nI He pointed out all of this to us;\n[over the luncheon table and then\nwent on to discuss his plans for\n\u2019Japan. The/e was no pity or sym-\nIpathy in his voice as he spoke. Nor\nwas there any of the cockiness of a.\nicomiueror. To put it simply he!\n[means to incapacitate Japan so far as!\nwar is concerned for generations to\ncome.\nAll Bark From China\nFor one thing, he means to bring\n\u2019every Jap back from China, and there\nFace-Lifting Is in the Works\nFor Huge Gotham Market\nWashington Market, Now a Confused Mass of Build\nings, Piers and Trucks, May Be Redesigned to Feed\nNew York More Efficiently\nNew York, Sept. 12\u2014(AP) \u2014About 9\nper cent of all the fnited States'\nfruits and vegetables\u2014l2,ooo,ooo\npounds per day\u2014goes through Wash\nington market, a sprawling, con\ngested area in lower Manhattan which\nsmells like yesterday\u2019s tossed vege\ntable sated.\nFew New Yorkers and fewer tour\nlets ever have seen Washington\nmarket That .state ot affairs mayi\nchange after a forthcoming face lift- i\nI Ing.\nWashington market lias been New\nYork's fruit and salad bowl since\n11813, and the history of trading on\nnearby downtown sites goes back to\nthe 1020 s, when a handful of settlers\nwaited on the Hudson's shores for\nI goods ferried over in Indian canoes.\nToday, produce streams Into the\nbursting market by rail, plane, boat\nand truck. The prices govern the j\ni prices for the nation.\ni The market is a loose term used to\nI describe some 145 000 square feet of\nI store space, and 150.000 square feet\nlof sidewalk in a 12-block-long, two\nblock-wide area occupied by 275 job\nbets, commission merchants and\nwholesalers. There are another hun-\ndeed or so brokers who use just office i\nspace.\nI At night, when business is heaviest.'\nthe market is a seething mass of i\nfeverish activity. Parked trucks, jut-1\ni ting diagonally from century-old di-I\nlapidated building, block littered\nstreets so narrow that a truck may\ntake several hours to go a few blocks.\n\u2018Some never get through at all, and\nI crates of lettuce, berries and celery\nmust be trundled along on handcartai\nby some of the 4000 market employes.\nSidewalks are dotted with sample\nI crates of produce and swarms of\nI buyers dickering with white-coated\nsalesmen. By day, the market is a,\n[soiled ghost, perfumed by the, fruits\nI and vegetables dropped and aquooshedi\nin the night's traffic.\nEvery one ot those antiquated\nbuildings, and several railroad piers,\nwould he demolished under the cur\nicnt plan to build a 42-mlllion dollar,\n57-acre modern terminal big enough\nhouse all the merchants and pro\nvide streamlined loading and unload\ning.\nThe new term nal would consist of\nHhujs 1420-foot platform building\nstruck the fall of the hardware ware\nhouse, where it burned furiously.\nFirenn n using chemicals and water\nconfined the blaze to the two build\nings, which still burned brightly an\nhour and a half after the planes fell\nat 9 p. m.\nCalvin E. Johnson, just released\nfrom the navy, and other volunteers\nwho reached the scene only moments\nafter the crash, said the flames al\nnady wire too high to save any of\nthe men aboard the craft.\nJohnson and Stephen Conrad, auxi\nliary policeman, pulled the body of\nthe* pilot out of one plane but It\nwas impossible to reach that in the\nofher machine because of fire.\nS. L. Devore and W. W. Rentiers\nof the Miami Herald stereotype de\npartment. eating lunch outside the\nnewspaper office, said they saw the\ntwo planes crash and fall.\n\"There were several planes in the\nair. and these two were flying courses\nthat crossed,\" said Devore. \"I saw\ntheir wings tangle and both planes\nplunged down.\nBefore I could see where they had\nfallen a brilliant fire sprang up from\nthe garage.\"\nare 4,000.000 of them, he says. In\nthe future they\u2019re going to live on\nthe four main Japanese islands. We\nasked if he thought the islands could\nsupport such an increased population.\nWell, they can die, cuin\u2019t they?\"\nMacArthur replied.\nThat didn't strike me as the words\nof a man who intends to be soft.\nAgain, while driving through the\nburned-out ruins of Yokohama, he\npointed to areas with such comments\nas, \"We killed thousands in that sec\ntion.\" He might just as well have\nbeen speaking of cabbages.\nFrom what Gen MacArthtir told us.\nit. was apparent that he does not\nwant to build up hatred in the Jap\nanese for Americans. He intends to;\nbreak the military caste that has had?\nJapan in its grip. He wants the i\npeople to have a taste of democracy,;\nto yroak down some of the age-old;\ntraditions by which they have pat-\nterned their lives.\nHe told us of his plans to pxtend\nsuffrage to the women of Japan, who!\nheretofore have raised their sons for,\none purpose only\u2014that of serving in\nthe armed forces.\nHe spoke of his plans for handling.\nthe prisoners of war and they fit into,\nthe general pattern he has laid down.\nHe said the foreign minister expressed.\nincredulity at the atrocity stories told I\nby allied prisoners. MacArthur prom-'\nised to provide conclusive proof.\nGoing one step further, the general\nsaid he was .considering having these\nprisoners tried in Japanese courts by\nJapanese judges and juries. In that\nway the Japanese would punish them\nselves and they could bear no grudge\nagainst rhe allies. I got the idea,\nhowever, that punishment would bo\nsevere.\nMeanwhile, we had an opportunity\nto observe the Japanese for them\nselves. One hesitates to pose as an\nexpert after only a two weeks\u2019 stay.\nin any country. But no one could\ndeny that the Japs were docile, that\nthey were whipped. What else was i\nlurking behind their poker faces we i\ncould only guess.\nBut one thing was certain: From,\nnow on they\u2019re going to take their\norders from the headquarters of Gen\nMacArthur. Ar.d so is Hirohito. If\nGen MacArthur says he can rule!\nthem with 200.000 troops, he can do\nit. His experience with the Japs\ndates back to 1904-05 when they\nwhipped Russia. He was a military\nobserver of that struggle and he has\nbeen watching them ever since.\ndirectly over the water, and generous\nfingers of store and delivery space\npointing inland, with 110 feet of\nstreet space between each one\u2014\nenough io allow trucks to back up\nfor loading, and still leave room fpr\ntwo traffic lanes.\nForty carfloats would be able to\ntie up at the platform. Hand loading\nand unloading would be eliminated\nby tractor-trailer trains used to con\nvty goods from the platform to whole\nsale stores and trucks. Ten acres ot\nparking space are calculated to take\ncare of all Incoming and outgoing\ntrucks.\nThomas Perrlch, market commis\nsion merchant, thinks the new plan\nwould sate at least 25 per cent un\nloading time, and points out that at\npresent it often takes three hours to\nunload and stack just 500, 50-pound\nbags of potatoes because o\"f parking\ndifficulties and hand loading. Sch\nwalb thinks it would save twice as\nmuch time and prevent much- waste\nof perishables.\nExactly how the new terminal,\ndesigned to feed the expected Metro\npolitan population In 1960. would be\nfinanced still is under, consideration\nBut New York's Mayor Florello H.\nLi Guardia has told market mer\nchants to run the new terminal them\nselves, and they are banking on a\nstibsidy front the Federal government\nto help them get the terminal under\nway.\nBOY\u2019S DFATH FOUND\nRESULT OF \u2018HEAT\u2019\nEldora, la.. Sept. 21\u2014(AP)\u2014A cor\noner's jury ruled today that the deapt\nof Ronald Miller. 17'-year-old Des\nMollit's inmate ot the State Training\nschool here, was \u201cthe result of heat\nprostration and possibly other com\nplications.\u201d but added that there was\nindication of any felonious act.\nThe jury returned Its verdict after\nhearing testimony from other inmates\nthat Miller was whipped, clubbed and\nblackjacked by school employes ns\npunishment for allegedly planning a\nmass escape from the Institution.'\nMurder charges have been filed\nagainst four school officials and cm\nployex in connection with the boy\u2019t\ndeath.\ni\nWLB HEAD OUITS\nANDBOARDGIVEN\nFULL AUTONOMY\nSecretary Schwellenbach\nActs Swiftly to Check More\nResignations\u2014Solons Of-\nfer New Plan for Settling\nLabor Disputes\nWashington, Sept. 20 (AP)\nChairman George W. Taylor of the\nWar Labor board turned in his res\nignation today and Labor Secretary\nSchwellenbach acted swiftly to head\noff further departures by granting\nthe WLB complete autonomy.\nAccepted With \u201cRegret\u201d\nLater the White House announced\nTaylor's resignation formally, mak\ning public correspondence in which\n^\u2019resident Truman accepted it \"with\nI regret\u201d effective October 15.\nTaylor wrote that for some time he\nhad been \u201canxious to reassume\u201d his\nregular duties. He is an economics\nprofessor at the University of Penn\nsylvania. Taylpr said he had been\nasked to stay until board duties in\ncident to the war program had been\ncompleted and \u201cthis assignment now\nhas been carried out.\u201d\nMr Truman expressed \"heartfelt\ngratitude for the efficiency and fidel\nity\" with which Taylor discharged his\nduties.\nThe October 15 date was under\nstood to have been arranged in order\nto give Schwellenbach time to work\nout with the retiring WLB chief the\nfitting of WLB into the labor depart\nment.\nGiven Former Independence\nSchwellenbach.' depending on the\nboard and a rejuvenated United States\nconciliation service to help him meet\nthe threat of widespread labor trou\nbles in the conversion to peacetime\nproduction, set forth a declaration of\npolicy which gives the board the same\ndegree of independence of action it\nhad as a war agencs\u2019.\nHe put his views In writing, at the\nrequest of the board member, for\nconsideration at an emergency ses\nsion of the WLB late today.\nThe President had given Schwel\nlenbach authority to formulate\npolicies for the board, a feature which\nsome members frankly did not care\nfor.\nWhile that disagreement was snarl\ning up the government's labor op\nerations, a broad new legislative plan\nfor voluntary settlement of worker\ndisputes was offered in Congress by\nfour senators.\nSenator McMahon (D-Ct) intro-\ndueed it with a claim that it would\nremove potential dangers from such\nstrike situations as now exist in De- 1\ntroit and other industrial centers.\nNew Legislative Plan\nThe legislation would center all es-\nforts toward settlement in the de-\npartmont of labor under a three-step\nprogram:\n1. Action by a division of media\ntion and conciliation within the de-\npartment. It would be composed of\nhighly paid experts from present\nagencies.\n2. Creation of a United States board\nof arbitration, an independent agency, i\nIt would act only when both parties'\nagreed to arbitration but once they\nagreed its decisions could become\njudgments in federal courts.\n3. Presidentially appointed boards\nof inquiry. These could step in even\nwhile strikes were under way to de\ntermine facts of public interest.\nThe Senate was told that the legis\nlation resulted from a series of closed\ndoor conferences with leading gov- i\neminent, labor and management offi\ncials.\" McMahon said these included\nformer Secretary of Labor Perkins,\nPresident William Green of the Amer\nican Federation of Labor, President\nIra Mosher of the National Associa-\ntion of Manufacturers, and members\nof various government boards and\nagencies dealing with labor problems.\nLessened anxiety was indicated here i\ntoday over the situation in Detroit\nautomobile plants, and among oil\nworkers, which had put pressure on\ngovernment agencies and speeded re\norganization. Both oil and automobile\nworkers want 30 per cent wage in- j\ncreases.\nPAY RAISE ASKED\nFOR SI\u2019S ABROAD\nOregon Senator Says \u2018Police\nDuty\u2019 Rates More Money\u2014\nVote Is Delayed On Re\ncruiting Measure\nWashington, Sept. 25\u2014(AP)\u2014De\nmands for higher pay for American\noccupation forces delayed Senate ac\ntion today on a recruiting bill aimed\nat raising a volunteer army and navy.\nSenator Morse (R-Or) protested\nagainst a vote before tomorrow. He\nsaid he wanted time to prepare\namendments.\nHe told reporters he had in mind:\u2014\n1. A pay raise for the army. He\nhad not decided on the amount.\n2. Extension of allotments to fami\nlies of soldiers until 18 months after\nrhe war is declared officially ended.\nUnder existing law. allotments would\nend six months after that declaration.\nMorse told the Senate It was one\nthing to ask men to serve in the\narmy for little pay when the country\nwas in danger and another to ask\nthat they do \"peacetime police duty\u201d\nfor low pay.\nTAX-CUTTING GROUP\nCONSIDERS PROGRAM\nHouse Ways and Means Com\nmittee Starts Big Task\nToday\nWashington. Sept. 25\u2014(AP) \u2014The\npeacetime tax-cutting mower was\noiled today for its first trial run.\nIt may:\n1. Clip 9.000,000 low-Income persons\nfrom the tax rolls.\n2. Cut the total Income tax bill of\nIndividuals by 22.000,000.000 or more.\n3. Eliminate or sharply reduce the\nwartime 95 per cent corporation ex\ncess profits tax.\nChairman Doughton (D-NC) an\nnounced the House ways and means\ncommittee will begin its first peace\ntime tax work tomorrow. November\n1 is the deadline for reducing levies\non 1916 individual and corporate in\ncome.\nBecause it's In a hurry the com\nmittee, which originates all tax legis\nlation probably won't hold public I\nhearings. Treasury Secretary Fred\nM Vinson probably will submit the\nadministration tax ideas In executive\nI session on Thursday.\nSome OPA Credit Bans End\nBut Most Are Still With Us\nHouse Repairs Now May Be Made On Credit Re\ntail Leaders Still Far From Satisfied\nNEW ARMY SCORES\nKEEP 300,000 MORE\nFROM OVERSEAS\nEnlisted Men Won\u2019t Be Sent\nif Their Points Exceed 36,\nor They\u2019re 37, or 34 With\nOne Year's Service\nWashington, Sept. 23\u2014(AP)\u2014The\nwar department inlay lowered thd\nscreening scores for shipment of of\nficers and enlisted men overseas, say\ning it made another 300,000 Ineligible^\nfor such duty.\nThe new scores, however, will not\napply to regular army personnel and\nvolunteers for overseas duty.\nEnlisted men will not be sent over\nseas, the department said in a state\nment. if their point score or age, ae\nof the September 2. 1915, computa\ntion is equal to or exceeds 36 points,\nor 37 years of age. or 34 years of age\nwith more than one year of service.\nOfficers will not be sent overseas,\nthe department added, if their point\nscore or ago, as of September 2, this\nyear, is equal to or exceeds:\nMale officers, except medical de\npartment officers. 48 points.\nMole officers, medical corps and\ni dental corps, 45 points or 40 years\nof age.\nMale officers, veterinary corps and\nI medical administrative corps, 30\npoints or 35 years of age.\nNurses, 12 points or 30 years of\ni age.\nMedical department dietitians and\nphysical therapy aides, 18 points or\n30 years of age.\nThe department added that Wom\nen's Army corps personnel will not\nbe sent abroad.\n225,000 IN N. Y.\ni REFUSE TO ENTER\nj PICKETED PLANTS\nOther Thousands Stay Home\nRather Than Walk Up to\nWork\u2014l 996 Buildings Af\nfected by Strike\nNew York, Sept. 25\u2014(AP)\u2014New\nYork city's strike of elevator and\nbuilding service men spread grad\nl ualiy today, effecting a slowly in\ncreasing paralysis over office, business\nand industrial activity.\nThe police estimate was that 1996\noffice and loft buildings were affected,\nI with more than 15,000 workers idle.\n[The strike began yesterday.\nThe Brooklyn and Bronx locals of\nthe AFL Building Service Employes'\nInternational union called meetings\nfor tonight to consider action.\n225,000 Observe I\u2019lckct. l ine\nThe Ladies\u2019 Garment Workers\u2019\nunion (independent) and the CIO In\nternational Fur Workers, with a\nI combined total of 225.000 members,\nwere idle, declining to pass picket\nlines.\nMeanwhile, the Railway Express\nAgency, Inc., announced it had or\ndered an embargo on incoming ex-\n\nexpress deliveries, as a direct result\niof the two-day strike. The embargo,\nthe company s^d. would apply to\nI New York city addresses, except in\ni Brooklyn and Staten Island.\nFirst arrest in the strike was re-\nI ported today when a striking woman\ni elevator operator was held on a dls\norderly conduct charge. Sho was ao\n[cused of attacking a nonunion em-\nI ployo of a financial district office\nbuilding.\nThe strike was called by local 32-B\nof the Service Employes\u2019 union fol\nlowing a Regional War Labor board\ndirective granting day workers $-\u20198.05\nI for a 44-hour week, instead of $30.15\nTor a 40-hour week, which had been\ni demanded. Previously the workers\n[were paid $30.15 for a 46-hour week.\nApartments Next\nApartment houses and hotels were\n'not affected by the strike, but David\nB. Sullivan, president of local 32-B,\n[told tenants of 1200 Manhattan apart\nments to prepare tor a work stop-\nI page.\nThousands of office workers In the\nEmpjre State, Life building, the Wool\nworth building and other skyscrapers\n[stayed home today, rather than climb\nthe stairs.\nIn several buildings, a union opera\ntor ran an elevator- for the sick to\n1 reach their physicians' offices, but the\ni doctors and their assistants had to\nclimb the stairways.\nSailors Aid Lnniber Strike\nPortland, Or.. Sept. 25\u2014(AP)\u2014The\n60,000 striking AFL Northwest Lum\nber Workers were notified today that\nAFL Sailors\u2019 union of the Pacific\nwould sail no ships with strike-bound\nlumber.\nA telegram from Harry Lunde\nberg, secretary-treasurer of the Sall-\nI ors\u2019 union at San Francisco, advised\nthat \u201cno member of our organization\n\u2018will sail ships into sawmills or docks\nwhere a bona fide AFL picket Une\nIs established.\u201d\nKenneth M. Davis, executive secre\ntary of the AFL Northwestern Coun\ncil of Lumber and Sawmill Workers,\nsaid the action would halt, a largo\ns^are of lumber movement. Long\nshoremen cannot load without a sail\nor aboard the vessel. The only other\ni sound today tn strike-stilled mills of\nfive states was a rumble of inter\nunion controversy over crossing picket\nI lines.\nDavid Beck, Seattle AFL teamster\nboss, reiterated his statement that\n[Washington teamsters would haul ro\ntall yard lumber which his fcllow-\nAFL leader has declared \u201chot cargo.\"\nWasp Kills Man\nAt Guilford, Ct.\nGuilford, Ct.. Sept. 25\u2014(AP)\u2014The\nsting of a wasp caused the death of:\nI Arthur Bengl, 82, Monday night,!\nIMe xtil Examiner F. DeWitt Smith\nsaid today.\nI Bengl. employed at the Shore Line\nIbus terminal here, requested that lie:\nbe driVen home shortly after he had\nreported for work. He complained of;\nI being 111 and said that he hud been\nstung by a wasp. A fellow employe\ndrove him to his home, but he was!\ndead upon arrival.\nDr Smith said that Bengl had been\n'allergic to Insect stings all of bls Ute\nand had several times\u2019 been confined,\nI to his bed because of bee stings.\nHe leaves his widow, five small\nchildren, tour sisters and two broth\ners.\nfcITONAL\nWashington, Sept. 25 (AD-The\ngovernment cleared away today its\nfinancial hurdle for obtaining new\ncoats of paint, furnace repairs, in\nsulation and general house renovation.\nIt lifted, as of October 15, all fed\neral credit controls for such home re\npair and improvements.\nIt took another step in the same\ndirection by extending from 12 to 18\nmonths the time in which borrowers\nmust repay \"nonpurpose\" loans\u2014\nthose for services or for general pur\nchases not on the government's re\nstricted list of 10 items.\nThis was viewed in some credit cir\ncles as an opening move toward com\nplete elimination of the consumer\ncredit restriction which was part of\n1 President Roosevelt\u2019s hold -the Une\nprogram.\nRemaining unchanged under 12-\nmonth credit control are items such\nas washing machines, vacuum clean\ners,- bed linen, mattresses, boats,\nwatches, cameras, automobiles, pianos\nand furniture.\nThe relaxation was not brought\nAbout without some opposition from\nOl\u2018A, which has consistently opposed\nletting up on the credit reins. Nor\ndid it receive the full approval of\nsome interested organizations which\nhave advocated the opposite extreme\n\u2014complete removal of the bans.\nThe Retail Credit institute issued\na statement that the Federal Reserve\nI board, which was responsible for the\nrelaxation, had \"brought forth a\n[mouse.\u2019\u2019 It repeated its assertion oft*\nI the past that, failure to remove the\niban> has constinued a \"gross dis\n:crimination among the American peo\nple\" in that it. did not provide for\nrenewal of purchases by lower income\ngroups of numerous necessities\nthrough long-term credit.\nRichard H. Stout, president, of the\nMorris Plan Bankers association, said\nin a statement that although \"any\nrelaxation of regulation is a definite\nstep in the right direction we\nfeel that there has not been any \\alid\nreason for continuance of regulation\nsince the machinery of price control\nand rationing was put into effect.**\nHe said that the relaxation was \"an\nimprovement\" but that he did not feel\nthat there was any reason for holding\n\"nonpurpose\" loans under the regula\ntion at all.\nSOUTHERN SOLONS\nOBJECT TO BOOST\nIN MINIMUM WAGE\nAfraid 65-Cent Level Would\n\u2018Destroy Southern Indus\ntry\u2019\u2014Labor Secretary Fa\nvors Increase\nWashington, Sept. 25 (AP)\nSouthern opposition to boosting the\nminimum wage cropped up today\nafter a Senate committee heard See\ni< i y of Labor Schwellenhach in\ndorse a proposed rise to 65 cents an\nhour.\nin a session which found senators\nqm-stiomng each other more often\nthan they did the witness. Senator\nEllender (D-La) repeatedly argued\nthat a wage increase would inevitably\nlead to increased living costs.\nHe contended, too. that a rise in\nprices would restrict exports anil\nhamper economic expansion.\nMore specifically, the Louisianan\nasserted:\n1. \"It might destroy southern in\ndustry.\u201d New Orleans had four cloth\ning factories when the present 40-\ncent. minimum was established In\n1938, now has but one.\n2. Sugar mills in Louisiana are\npaying 40 cents, \u201cmaybe 45,\u201d and the\nprice of sugar would have to rise \u201cif\nthey arc forced overnight to go to 65.\u201d\nThere were signs that Ellender'a\nfears were entertained by some other\nsoutherners and that the bill would\nface rough going.\nNevertheless. Senators Aiken (R-\nVt) and Tunnell (D-Del), members of\nthe labor subcommittee conducting\nthe hearings, predicted that Congress\nwill approve some increase in th\u00bb,\nexisting wage floor. President Tru\nman has recommended an increase.\nSenator Pepper (D-Fla) introduced\nthe pending bill for himself and Sen\nators Kilgore (D-WVa), Myers (D\n---I\u2019ai Wagner (D-NY). Chavez <D\nNM). Magnuson (D-Wash). Guffey\n(D-Pa). Mead (D-NY). Murray (D-\nMont) ami Elbert Thomas (D-Utah).\nIt provides for a 65-cent minimum\nwage In the first year after enact\nment. 70 cents in the second year\nand 75 in the third.\nFLORIDA SOFTENS\n\u2018SWEATBOX\u2019 LIFE\nSolitary Confinement Cells\nNot to Have Space Cut m I\nHalf During Day but Won't\nBe Eliminated\nTallahassee. Fla.. Sept 25 (AP)\nThe Florida cabinet today voted\nHo knock the daytime partitions out\nof prison camp solitary confinement\ncells which have drawn criticism aa\nsweatboxes.\u201d The action means con\nvicts \u201cin solitary\" will have room\nto' lie down, stand up or sit during i\nI the day as well as al night.\nCommissioner of Agriculture Na*\nthan Mayo, head ot the prison eys\ntern recommended elimination of the\npartition^ which force prisoners to J\nstand or sit down during the day.\nAt the same time, he defended use of\nthe device for punishment and said\n\"there Is no such thing as a sweat\nbox in Florida.\u201d\nSupt L. F. Chapman of the state'\nt rjaon said \"some prisoners are In\nsurrectionists, rebels against author\nllty\u201d and that solitary confinement was\nthe best way to handle them.\n\"II we atsindoned the confinement\ncell. what, method of discipline would\n[you have?\" Gov Caldwell asked.\n\"Why. take him down and put him\nin bed and give him a novel to read,\ni 1 suppose.\" Mayo replied.\nPresent regulations fo.r use of the s\n[confinement cells and their dimtn\n[slops have been In effect since 1923,\nshortly after Floriday abolished whip\nping as punishment and ended the i\n[old system of leasing convivia to\n[private individuals and firms for\nwork, Mayo said.\nThey provide that the cells must\nbe 61- feet long, three feet wide and\nseven feet from the floor to the grilled\nventilation openings near the root.\nDuring the day, heretofore, partitions\nhave been put in from top to bot\ntom to cut the floor space In half.\nAtty-Gen Tom Watson, who had\nmoved at an earlier meeting th,i^\ntheir use lie abandoned altogetl ir,\nsaid today he thought they were ln\nl humane.\"","height":"26021","width":"19529"}}
